text.tspan: Behavioral reliability of cells in complex signaling environments
Adam Coster, Steven Altschuler, and Lani Wu

flowRoot.flowPara: Tissues within multicellular organisms demonstrate behavioral reliability. Though recent in vitro work has uncovered a high level of unpredictability in single cell behaviors [1], population-averaged behaviors often are predictable (Fig.1).

Interestingly, small functional units of tissues, such as the intestinal crypt, have too few cells to rely on population-averaged responses (Fig. 2), yet still show robust behavior. Thus, single cells must be capable of more reliable signal processing than in vitro experiments suggest. The evidence that individual cells are poor communicators is based on experiments that stimulate cells with single ligands of varying concentration, but cells in a physiological setting are normally bathed in a plethora of signals.
Hypothesis: Crosstalk among signaling pathways, activated by complex mixtures of environmental signals, increases the predictability of single cell behaviors.

text.tspan: Green Center for Systems Biology, University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas TX

flowRoot.flowPara: FIGURE 1: Cells respond predictably as a population but unpredictably as individuals. (Left) The population response of NFkB to TNFA increases with dose, but (middle, right) individual cells show a large diversity of responses. Human Colonic Epithelial Cells (HCECs ) treated for 40 minute with Tumor Necrosis Factor (TNFA) and immunostained with NFkB-P65 (column 2 in Fig. 3). >500 cells quantified per TNFA dose, using method shown in Fig. 4. Circles, medians; lines, SD. Black circle, dose shown in histogram. Scalebar, 10Î¼m.
These observations lead to a surprising paradox: Why do cells respond unpredictably to a single signal in vitro, yet respond reliably to complex environmental signals in vivo?

flowPara.flowSpan: FIGURE 3: Multiplexed ligands emulate the increased complexity seen in vivo. Changes in downstream readout variability represent changes in signaling reliability. (Top) Cells are treated with all combinations of 4 ligands, and each canonical downstream target is immunostained. Each column is a treatment combination. 0/1 indicates absence/presence of each ligand. (Bottom) Cartoon. Complex and simple inputs are expected to yield differing output variability, due to crosstalk.

flowRoot.flowPara: FIGURE 4: Nuclear translocation of ligand targets in single cells is measured by immunofluorescence imaging, automated image segmentation, and quantification of pixels values in segmented regions. (Top left) Sample cropped images showing Smad2/3. (Top right) Nuclear (green) and perinuclear (blue) segmentation. (Bottom) Histograms of all cells from each treatment (n>1000), showing high Smad2/3 response variability and overlap with control. HCECs treated 40min +/- 10ng/mL TGFB (column 5 in Fig. 3). Scalebar, 20 micron.

FIGURE 5: Changes in response reliability can be measured using mutual information. (Top) Mutual information (MI) increases as distributions separate (HCECs treated with TGFB, 40min). (Bottom) Cartoon. If it is true that complexity increases reliability, then treated distributions (+) should separate further from untreated (-) with more ligands. This would be measured as an increase in mutual information.
Individual cells unreliably respond to single ligands in vitro, but are reliable in complex physiological conditions.
Crosstalk between pathways may allow for reliable responses in complex signaling environments.
Mutual information serves as a measurement of reliability.
Quantification of reliability within many combinations of multi-ligand environments will reveal the relationship between complexity, crosstalk, and signaling reliability.
